Introduction ¶

Los Angeles is a big city that must spend a significant of its resources to prevent crime in the streets. LA Police officers has the responsibility to guarantee security and prevent major incidents in the city. However, due the enormous amount of crimes happening every day in Los Angeles, watching all the citizens becomes a challenging task for the force. For this reason, technology development such as machine learning models can be useful to identify future crimes based on historical incidents. This study will propose a machine learning model to identify risk areas for crime based on historical features of LA police crime dataset from 2020.

Dataset Source ¶

The LA crime dataset contains crime records of the LAPD (Los Angeles Police Department) from 2020. The data was sourced from Data Catalog(LAPD,2023)

Dataset Details ¶

The dataset contains observations of reported crimes in Los Angeles from 2020 until the last update the 25th of March of 2023. These records contain unique ID of the incident, date of the occurrence, Area, geographic location. Additionally, each record has information about the demography of the victim and the type of crime. This set of variables can be helpful to model predictions of areas sensible to crime.

The LA Crime Dataset has 28 features and 690,454 observations. However, the following variable will be excluded because most of them are equal to the main variable but with a different structure. Also, a few variables could generate noise in the model because the uniqueness of their values.

Target Feature ¶

For this model, the target feature will be the AREA code of LAPD. This target will predict the area when the next crime occurs based on historical information of crimes and demography of victims.

Problem Statement

Los Angeles Police Department has 21 community police stations working on the security of citizens and visitor of Los Angeles. LADP has the responsibility to prevent or to reduce victim crimes in the city. For this reason, predictive models can be potential tools to optimize the deployment of police force across the LA in a efficient manner. For example, if the Police Department simulates a crime with certain specification such as victim sex, victim age, time of the day and day of the week, etc., It will be able to identify the area where the crime will occur. As a result, depending of the type of crime, the department can deploy the efficient number of police officers to the area and they can prevent crimes in optimal manner.

Thus, the goal of this project is to propose a predictive model to identify vulnerable areas based on historical crime information and descriptive features. This goal can be reached by completing these three objectives. Firstly, Prepare the dataset for analysis and model by preproccesing the features. Secondly, Analyse the LAPD dataset by descriptive statistics and visualisations to comprehend values behave in each variable and relationships between the features. Finally, predict susceptible areas for crime based on historical information collected from the Police Department.

  • Identification of mission values

There is a significant quantity of missing values within the features of victim_sex,victim_age and weapon_used_code. premis_code only has 8 missing values.

In [8]:

It is possible to assume that missed values for victim_sex and victim_age are human error at the moment of police report. As a result, this observation will be removed from the analysis to improve consistency in the dataset. However,

weapon_used_code missing values required different assumption. There are two points to consider, (1) not all crimes required of a weapon to be committed and (2) a null value could be considered as an $Unknown$ which has the code 500. For this reason, instead of removing these missing values, they were classified as 500 weapon_used_code. Finally, the victim_sex feature is filtered to removed values "H" and "X" because these values are not able to describe any profile of the victims. The entry process could had mistakes.

These changes reduced the dataset from 690,454 rows to 516,988 rows

In [9]:
# Removing missing values
df_1 = df_i.dropna(subset=["vict_sex","vict_descent","premis_code"])


# Filling NaN values with category code 500.0 within weapon_used_code
df_1["weapon_used_code"]=df_1["weapon_used_code"].fillna(500.0)

# Victim age > 0
df_1 = df_1[df_1['vict_age'] >0]

# Victim sex re labelling
df_1 = df_1[df_1["vict_sex"]!="H"]
df_1 = df_1[df_1["vict_sex"]!="X"]
df_i['vict_sex']=pd.Categorical(df_i['vict_sex'])

print("The new shape of the dataset after removing missing values",df_1.shape)

Literature Review ¶

The massive increment in criminal records demands that police departments develop and deploy technology to prevent criminal activities. Data science developments can help to create technological tools for the analysis of criminal records by applying different machine learning paradigms. As evidence, many studies of supervised machine learning techniques have proposed models to predict future instances of crime based on the type of features and the objective variable (Bshayer, et al., 2020). Although there are many possible models, this paper will explain predictive models for crime prevention based on these three ML paradigms information-based, probability-based and similarity-based.

Criminology is a science that studies the demographic and social aspects of a crime. This field extracts information to investigate crimes and predicts future occurrences based on criminal records. For this reason, police and similar security institutions require criminal analysis with statistical outputs to determine crime patterns that may help to anticipate future occurrences. For instance, a police department can identify vulnerable areas for crime and common victim profiles by descriptive analysis of historical data. As result, security institutions require technology applied to criminal analysis to reduce the number of felonies.

Then, machine learning is a useful instrument to be added to criminal analysis because it can assist with forecasting essential information about crime events by applying predictive models. To aim this, the selection of features, objective variables and ML paradigms are crucial steps within the predictive data analysis lifecycle. This is because crime prediction in real-time is a challenging task that may contain multiple dimensions of space (GPS position, area, region), time (date, time) and explanatory factors (social demography of the crime, victim profile) to generate the final set of solutions (M. Wawrzyniak, et al., 2018). Therefore, there are a large number of models for crime detection regarding the ML paradigm.

Firstly, information-based learning can be applied to crime prediction models with categorical or numerical variables. Algorithms based on decision tree theory may offer relevant solutions when the target variable is the space of the occurrences or the amount of occurrences per day. For example, Zhang, Liu, Lan, Song, Xiao & Chen (2022) proposed to predict the number of thefts within an area by analysing the area features (Area containing certain population age, restaurant area, department store, etc.) and applying XGBoost algorithm which is a learning method able to build different types of decision trees and flexible to configurate. Another example of a data-driven crime detection model is proposed by M. Wawrzyniak et al. (2018), who have built an algorithm using Neural Networking to predict the number of crime occurrences per day by interconnecting time series data of criminal records and exogenous variables of different instances.

Secondly, the probabilistic approach can contribute to the classification of future crimes. Naïve Bayes is a probability-based algorithm that can be used in categorical features to classify if the feature is applicable or not for the observation. For instance, Khan, M., Ali, A., & Alharbi, Y. (2022) studied the efficiency of Naïve Bayes model to forecast the probability of violent or nonviolent crimes. Although the study did not show the best results for the Naïve Bayes model, it illustrates the possibility to use probabilistic ML paradigms to classify criminal variables.

Finally, Clustering models are an alternative to classify crime occurrences by applying genetic algorithms within the formula. GA’s are algorithms that improve their accuracy by evolving their fitness function. As evidence, Kiani, R., Mahdavi, S., & Keshavarzi, (2015) applied this idea by improving outlier detection before processing the data and defining a fitness function on the accuracy and classification error parameters. As a result, it is possible to predict the number of occurrences by the classification of crimes.

In conclusion, police departments may have significant benefits from predictive models no matter the paradigm. This is because machine learning can contribute essential information to classify and predict felonies. For this reason, it is vital to select the correct features to make of predicting real-time crime less challenging and more accurate.

Conclusions ¶

In summary, Los Angeles Police Department criminal records is a dataset with more than 600,000 observations from 2020. This information was pre proccessed by removing missing value and re classifying features variables. This actions were neccessary in order to obtain clean and tidy data as much as the information collected allows it. After the pre processing, the number records was reduced to a sample of 28,850 criminal records by random selection. Finally, the descriptive analysis showed the following insights:

  • There areas more affected than others among the 21 divided areas of LA
  • In general the average range of victims age is 30 to 40 years old
  • There are areas where female population is more affected than male population
  • The average female victim age is lower than the average male victim age
  • The area 1 of Los Angeles is the most affected by crime of different kind.

In conclusion, the LAPD requires of a technological development that helps to predict which area is more vulnerable to have crime occurrences depending of the type of crime, day and time. For this reason a Machine Learning model able to use the feature variables of time, space and descriptive variables to forecast areas is a neccesity to optimise the distribution of the police force in each of these areas depending of their level of risk.
